[
    {
        "content": "<p>A lot is known about existence of pushouts in some notable categories like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Cat}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Cat</span></span></span></span></span>. Is anything known about whether all pushouts exist in the category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>l</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{2Cat}_{lx}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8361em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">2Cat</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> of 2-categories and lax functors?</p>\n<p>I've had a cursory look online and on nLab but couldn't find any references.</p>",
        "id": 389127791,
        "sender_full_name": "Bruno Gavranović",
        "timestamp": 1693900847
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Almost certainly they don't, but it would take some work to find a counterexample.</p>",
        "id": 389193488,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1693921517
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What makes you say that? I know lax functors often behave badly, but I can't tell what goes wrong with pushouts (or say, colimits here in general), but doesn't go wrong in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Cat}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Cat</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 389342505,
        "sender_full_name": "Bruno Gavranović",
        "timestamp": 1693979269
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm aware that this category hosts 2-dimensional things (2-cats, lax functors), and I imagine it might be too strict to ask of it to have 1-pushouts.<br>\nOn the other hand, I've been surprised before, for instance, when learning about what the right notion of a 2-cell here is.</p>",
        "id": 389342657,
        "sender_full_name": "Bruno Gavranović",
        "timestamp": 1693979372
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In general, categories of algebras for a 2-monad and lax morphisms don't have all limits and colimits, even in a 2-dimensional sense.   Intuitively, I tend to think of this as being \"because\" the morphisms in these categories are not just those that \"preserve\" some structure, but are <em>themselves</em> structure.</p>",
        "id": 389345638,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1693981061
    }
]